postcontent:
I have bought and sold quite a few firearms on Armslist. 99% of the people I have come in contact with have been really good people. 

If I price my gun for sale too high, it will not get sold. Simple economics. It's value is what it will sell for, right?

I have to chuckle when people email me in a degrading way and tell me a price is too high. Who the fuck cares?

Convertibles, bikes cycles in the summer, Ski lodges in the winter, trendy restaurants, hot concert tickets...yeah all worth more than face value. 

If you don't like the price, don't buy it. Simple.

There are no markings except 2 notches carved on the under side of the barrel. The very tip of the hammer was broken off a long time ago. Send me an offer! Willing to ship.

Parlor pistols and rifles (zimmerschutzen from German, "room marksman" or "room shoot") were popularized in the mid to late 19th Century, particularly in the Germanic countries, as a way to entertain guests, have family fun, and to increase one's shooting skills. Generally heavy barreled and often elaborately engraved rifles (zimmerbusche) were produced for clearly upscale clients. These generally used a Flobert (CB-Cap) cartridge chambered a few inches from the muzzle. Sometimes equally elaborate parlor pistols (zimmerpistole) were chambered for Flobert cartridges or simply used a percussion cap. In this country, a small, almost toylike parlor pistol was briefly manufactured by Remington in 1860.

title: For Sale:  3 Mosin Nagant 91/30 Bolt Action Rifles
postcontent:
Unloading a few of my Mosin's... All three are Izhevsk manufactured and each has a different little quirk to make it unique. These have not been cleaned of the cosmoline yet. They'll go to you the way they came to me which means they each come in their own cardboard box with the following accessories: 2 ammo pouches, a bayonet, a sling, and the accessory/cleaning kit. Perfect for starting your own Mosin collection! All have good or better bores that just need some cleaning and none have been counterbored. I can and will check the headspace on each before you purchase it.

1. 1943 - This is most definitely a war time stock. Deep dark colored shellac with the usual slight flaking and wear you'd expect on the war time stocks. No refurb mark on the stock at all. Has an unusually beefy looking trigger and a few faint stock cartouches still intact. Kinda my favorite of the bunch because it has the "been there" look on the stock but the metal is in excellent shape.

2. 1942 #1 - Also a war time stock but much lighter finish and none of the war time flakiness in the shellac. This one has a few stock repairs. Lots of various stamps on the stock along the hand grips and a light circular cartouche on the butt.

3. 1942 #2 - This one wears a refurb stock with the [/] mark on it. Still has the protective tape soaked in cosmoline on the hand guard from the refurb process. A few stock cartouches (mostly numbers) are stamped on this one as well.

Let me know which one you're interested in and I can send detailed photos. Price is $125 per rifle and that includes the accessories as mentioned. If you're new to the Mosin thing feel free to ask any questions you have. I am a C&R license holder so I will need your info for my log book and will provide a bill of sale.
